<div id="review_649779191" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/649779191" />
    <a title="Rose" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/278701-rose"><img alt="Rose" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1496848953p2/278701.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/649779191?book_show_action=true">Jun 24, 2013</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Rose" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Rose" href="/user/show/278701-rose">Rose</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/278701-rose?shelf=vampire">vampire</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer649779191" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4200718250816918764">Interesting take on vampire lore. This was actually 5 novellas strung together by one vampire being the main character. Each novella is told from a different perspective. My favorite was the 3rd story in which our vampire sees a psychiatrist about his &quot;illusion&quot; of being a vampire. The story really gets interesting once she figures out his illusion is no illusion at all. <br/><br/>I enjoyed the idea of vampire not being a supernatural being, nor a being with super hero abilities, but a creature who just s</span>
  <span id="freeText4200718250816918764" style="display:none">Interesting take on vampire lore. This was actually 5 novellas strung together by one vampire being the main character. Each novella is told from a different perspective. My favorite was the 3rd story in which our vampire sees a psychiatrist about his "illusion" of being a vampire. The story really gets interesting once she figures out his illusion is no illusion at all. <br /><br />I enjoyed the idea of vampire not being a supernatural being, nor a being with super hero abilities, but a creature who just survives on cleverness and cunning. Weyland is forever and immortal, he needs to create a life and act as though human amongst his prey. He remains always distant and aloof never letting anyone get close. To him, you do not form relationships with mere cattle which is your food. Weyland has had many lives and existences before now, however he does not remember any of them. He later learns why and it is heartbreaking. The vampire can be out in the day, does not have the usual garlic and stake legend affect him. He does not eat food, and he has no fangs. His way of feeding is actually very cool. He is a one of a kind creature who is definitely lonely, only he does not know it. <br /> <br /><br />I did not care for my first protagonist in the first story. She almost put me off reading this, but once past her, I as fine. I also wasnt super thrilled with the 4th story only because the great detail of Tosca was too much. I understand its relevancy here, but it went on a bit too long for me. I get it, point made, move on.<br /><br />I recommend to all who love vampires and are willing to view it in a different light.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="4200718250816918764" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


