  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_1222630512" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1222630512" />
    <a title="Wendy Bousfield" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/20388365-wendy-bousfield"><img alt="Wendy Bousfield" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1394119553p2/20388365.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1222630512?book_show_action=true">Mar 09, 2015</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Wendy Bousfield" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Wendy Bousfield" href="/user/show/20388365-wendy-bousfield">Wendy Bousfield</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/20388365-wendy-bousfield?shelf=vampires">vampires</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1222630512" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11639058538800369049">Charnas has written a psychological “What if?” story. She asks: How would a being who lives for centuries and subsists on human blood construct a plausible persona in the 20th century? Charnas also explores the corresponding question: How would the people with whom this alien being comes in contact respond to him psychologically? <br/><br/>During the latter half of the 20th century, the vampire takes the identity of Dr. Weyland, a distinguished professor of anthropology at Cayslin University. Because his </span>
  <span id="freeText11639058538800369049" style="display:none">Charnas has written a psychological “What if?” story. She asks: How would a being who lives for centuries and subsists on human blood construct a plausible persona in the 20th century? Charnas also explores the corresponding question: How would the people with whom this alien being comes in contact respond to him psychologically? <br /><br />During the latter half of the 20th century, the vampire takes the identity of Dr. Weyland, a distinguished professor of anthropology at Cayslin University. Because his intelligence, longevity, and nonhuman nature give him unique perspectives on human civilization, Dr. Weyland has become a distinguished anthropologist. Distanced from culture-bound assumptions and distracting emotional entanglements, Weyland devotes himself to anthropological research and to preying on unsuspecting humans.<br /><br />The first three chapters are from the POV of humans who come to realize Weyland’s vampire nature, while the last two are from the POV of Dr. Weyland himself. In “The Ancient Mind at Work,” the South African housekeeper of the Cayslin faculty club, Mrs. De Groot, observes Dr. Weyland’s vampiric attack on a student. (Usually, Weyland does not kill his victims when he drinks blood.) Aware that de Groot is watching him, Weyland attacks her. De Groot shoots Weyland, who manages to escape in his car. The descendent of white South Africans, who survive by preying on blacks, she is prepared to defend herself.<br /><br />The next chapter, “The Land of Lost Content,” is from the POV of Mark, a 15-year-old boy, spending the summer with his Uncle Roger, a petty criminal and fence. Roger imprisons the wounded vampire in his apartment, planning to sell him to Alan Reese, a Satanist who wants to render Weyland helpless so as to use him (in an unspecified way) for his May Eve Sabbat. One of several people who feel intense sympathy for Weyland, Mark feeds the vampire his own blood and helps him escape.<br /><br />The narrator of the third chapter, “Unicorn Tapestry,” is a psychotherapist, Floria (named after the heroine of TOSCA), who sees Weyland as a patient. (Having left Cayslin under the pretext of having had a mental breakdown, Weyland seeks a formal confirmation that he can resume professorial duties.) Weyland explains honestly and fully to Floria what being a vampire is like. The two become lovers.<br /><br />In the final chapters, Weyland has joined the Anthropology Department of the University of New Mexico. Reminded of his lover Floria, he is unexpectedly moved by seeing TOSCA at the Santa Fe Opera.<br /><br />At the very end of VAMPIRE TAPESTRY, Dr. Weyland, is out of options. No longer is able to continue his masquerade as an eccentric but human college professor, he enters one of his periodic hibernations. Only at the end of this “life” does Weyland experience affection for any of the beings he has preyed upon. Up until this point in the novel, I had found VAMPIRE TAPESTRY rather a cerebral experience. When Weyland suddenly experiences empathy for people who had loved him, I was genuinely moved.<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="11639058538800369049" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

